<br>
OO programming isn't a magic programming model that cures what ailes ya. A common mistake for people who have first learned how the OO model works is to go crazy with it and try to use it <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>everywhere</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, when in a lot of cases, it simply doesn't apply.<br>
<br>
But, to get to the point, it probably doesn't have anything to do with server downtime, anyway. Building a program using, say, a simple modular approach doesn't in any way prevent you from compiling and linking separate parts of the program independantly from one another. Headers and libraries are what are responsible for that, not OO.<br>
<br>
At any rate, it's not as if the programmers are writing the code during the patch time (at least, I sure as heck <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>hope</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> they're not!). The patch downtime is simply the amount of time it takes them to do the push, and to do any cleanup if they realize that a show-stopping bug got through. Most of the patches only take a couple hours, which is about what you would expect for that kind of thing. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=jaranna>Jaranna</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 487<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(4/23/03 8:11:15 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3074.topic&index=20>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: EQ PET PEVES</span><hr size=1> It's a simple question of pissing off the least amount of people.  The vast majority of EQ players are in the United States.  So, they choose a time when the least amount of people are awake (early in the morning) and patch then.<br>
<br>
Does it suck that the Europeans and everyone else can't play?  Yep.  But imagine the CS nightmare they'd have if they brought the servers down at 6 p.m. for a six- to eight-hour patch.<br>
